TY  - JOUR
AU  - Matsa, David A.
T1  - Competition and Product Quality in the Supermarket Industry*
PY  - 2011
Y1  - 2011/08/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qjr031
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 126
IS  - 3
SP  - 1539
EP  - 1591
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - This article analyzes the effect of competition on a supermarket firm's incentive to provide product quality. In the supermarket industry, product availability is an important measure of quality. Using U.S. Consumer Price Index microdata to track inventory shortfalls, I find that stores facing more intense competition have fewer shortfalls. Competition from Walmart—the most significant shock to industry market structure in half a century—decreased shortfalls among large chains by about a third. The risk that customers will switch stores appears to provide competitors with a strong incentive to invest in product quality.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qjr031
ER  - 



